  Let \(X\) be a finitely generated \(\Lambda\)-module. If \(X[T]=0\) and \(X/TX\) is a free \(\mathbb{Z}_p\)-module of rank \(r\), then \(X\) is a free \(\Lambda\)-module of rank \(r\).

  \textit{Proof idea.} Use Nakayama to produce a surjection \(\Lambda^r\twoheadrightarrow X\), then compare modulo \(T\). The condition \(X[T]=0\) kills the kernel after reduction, and a second Nakayama argument shows that the kernel is already zero.
\end{lemma}

